posts.name: 8oz Burger and Co.
posts.note: 8oz Burger and Co. is an upscale burger joint offering all-natural burgers and craft cocktails amid cowboy-themed decor. NOTE: They have a few locations.

posts.name: A + Hong Kong Kitchen
posts.note: From their Facebook page, 'At A + Hong Kong Kitchen, our goal is to bring traditional Hong Kong style cuisine along with creative fusion dishes to Seattleites as well as travelers from all around the world. In this cozy space located in the heart of the International District, we are here to provide not just a simple snack that satisfy your immediate crave, but also a delicious meal that is remarkable and can fulfills your stomach. Last but not least, try some of our homemade delicate desserts to supplement your glucose level. Hong Kong cuisine is mainly influenced by Cantonese cuisine. But since Hong Kong was once a colony of British, many western elements are found in Hong Kong cuisine. It is not surprised you complete your Hong Kong cuisine meal with spaghetti and steaks. Of course, those dishes are so- call &ldqou;Hong Kong style.&rdqou;'
posts.rcmmnd: Best Chinese restaurant in every state from MSN website

posts.name: Ada's Technical Books and Cafe
posts.note: Ada's Technical Books and Cafe is a bright, airy cafe inside a self-described 'geeky' bookstore offering light, health-conscious fare. The kitchen is open from 8:00 AM until 5:00 PM, while the cafe provides coffee, pastries, and grab and go items until the bookstore closes for the night.

posts.name: Annapurna Cafe
posts.note: Annapurna Cafe serves the traditional dishes of India, Nepal, and Tibet are served in a colorful underground room with a bar.

posts.name: Beecher's Handmade Cheese
posts.note: Beecher's Handmade Cheese is where you can view of cheese-making plus quick comfort food like mac 'n' cheese in a snug space with eating bar. I liked their cheese curd that is squeaky when you chew it.

posts.name: Big Mario's Pizza
posts.note: Big Mario's Pizza serves generous, NYC-style pizza slices, cocktails, and beer in a laid-back space with a retro, dive-bar vibe. From the Seattle Eater website, 'Headed east out of Ballard and across Leary Way, bikers have quick access to this popular local mini-chain, which dishes up New York-style pizza, served by the slice and in whole pie form. Known for its divey vibe, Big Mario’s menu is divided equally between meat pies (featuring the Mai Tai with pineapple and Italian ham) and veggie, like the Pear Gorgonzola. For those getting a slice to go, Bad Jimmy’s Brewing Co. next door is not a bad place to camp out for a beer.' NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Bizzarro Italian Cafe
posts.note: Bizzarro Italian Cafe is a lively, long-running Italian eatery serving trattoria fare in a funky space with eclectic decor. The items to order are the pasta and seafood or the elk in ravioli.

posts.name: Bok a Bok Fried Chicken
posts.note: Bok a Bok Fried Chicken is a pocket-sized space for Korean fried chicken and biscuits with comfort food-inspired side dishes. After watching Diner's Drive-ins and Dives they reocmmend the Bowl of Shame or the Sesame Soy Garlic Chicken Sandwich. NOTE: They have multiple location.

posts.name: Brouwer's Cafe
posts.note: Brouwer's Cafe is a hip pub offering Belgian-style grub, hundreds of beers, and over 50 scotches in a former warehouse. For over ten years Brouwer’s Café has been one of Seattle’s most sought-out craft beer destinations.

posts.name: Canlis
posts.note: Canlis is a landmark fine-dining destination (since the 1950s) offering Pacific NW fare in a mid-century-modern home. From their website, 'The opportunity to meet and serve you is one we don’t take lightly. Not for the past three generations, at least. Come spend an evening. Our favorite thing in the world is taking care of others, and few places can do it quite like Canlis. NOTE: Attire: Go big. Dress up. Make a statement. You're beautiful, let it show! We are a dress-respectful restaurant. No casual or athletic attire, please. Men will feel most comfortable in a suit or sport coat.

posts.name: Dacha Diner
posts.note: Dacha Diner is a bright, convivial space serving up classic Jewish/Eastern European comfort food and cocktails. From the Seattle times website, 'Dacha describes its menu as “Eastern European and Jewish cuisine.” The place is run by the trio behind The Independent Pizzeria, an undersung local hero of the form in Madison Park. Given their skill with that, then, arguably, what you ought to go eat immediately is Dacha’s Adjarian khachapuri, a traditional Georgian cheesy-bread-boat that may, if such a thing is possible, represent an improvement upon pizza.'

posts.name: Dahlia Bakery
posts.note: Dahlia Bakery is a snug bakery serving breakfast fare and pastries along with sandwiches and signature coconut cream pie. From their website, 'Home to the world-famous Triple Coconut Cream Pie, Tom Douglas’ Dahlia Bakery offers artisan breads, handmade pastries, and cakes which are baked daily in small batches. Breakfast and lunch options created by the Dahlia chef team, start at breakfast with bacon and organic eggs and finish the day with a quart of Tom's Tasty Tomato soup and a loaf of fresh-baked bread.' Also, from the Seattle Eater website, 'Even if renowned Seattle chef Tom Douglas’s triple coconut cream pie is not your bag, Dahlia Bakery in Belltown still delivers. The list of egg sandwiches is enough to bring any breakfast lover to happy tears, and the pastries are truly the best excuse around to eat dessert first. And seriously, have you given that coconut cream pie a shot?'

posts.name: Din Tai Fung
posts.note: Din Tai Fung was initially founded as a cooking oil retail business in 1958; Din Tai Fung was reborn as a steamed dumpling and noodle restaurant in 1972. Din Tai Fung gives people throughout the world the opportunity to experience a classic “taste of Taiwan.” I need to get the soup dumplings (XiaoLongBao) when I get a chance to eat here. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: DeLaurenti Food and Wine
posts.note: DeLaurenti Food and Wine is an Italian food & wine shop selling cheeses, meats and imported groceries plus a cafe for light bites. You need to grab some cured meats to take home with you along with grabbing one or both of their meat cones to snack on for $8.00 a piece. They have a Skillet's Balsamic and brown sugar bacon jam

posts.name: Dick's Drive-In
posts.note: Dick's Drive-In has been open since 1954 and is the original of a chain dishing out burgers, fries, and hand-dipped shakes along with being open late. From their website, 'Setting the standard for the best fast food in Seattle was precisely the intent of the three partners who started Dick’s. “Our goal,” says Dick Spady, the last surviving partner, “was simply to serve fresh, high-quality food at low prices with instant service.” NOTE: They have multiple locations.'

posts.name: Dong Thap Noodles
posts.note: Dong Thap Noodles makes fresh in-house noodles that are prepared every morning. Pho noodles, Udon, Bun Bo, Pad Thai, Thin Vermicelli noodles are made fresh daily from scratch. They are the home of the Pho Super Bowl Challenge.

posts.name: Ellenos Real Greek Yogurt
posts.note: Ellenos Real Greek Yogurt is a family-owned shop offering classic handcrafted Greek yogurt infused with modern flavors and toppings. NOTE: They have multiple locations and are in other places too.

posts.name: Elliot’s Oyster House
posts.note: Elliot’s Oyster House is a waterfront restaurant with a bay view known for its selection of oysters and sustainable seafood. You need to order the Salmon Ruben.

posts.name: Ezell's Famous Chicken
posts.note: Ezell's Famous Chicken is a local fast-food chain known for its home-made fried chicken plus down-home sides and desserts. I had their chicken tenders, fries, and mini rolls from their food truck. I'm looking forward to going to one of their stores. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Fair Start Restaurant
posts.note: Fair Start Restaurant serves lunch and occasional dinners as part of a work training program for the homeless.

posts.name: General Porpoise Doughnuts
posts.note: General Porpoise is a charming Renee Erickson spot serving handmade donuts and coffee from hard-to-find roasters. From their website, 'Doughnuts at General Porpoise are made with fresh eggs and are filled with seasonal jams, jellies, curds, custards, and creams. In addition to doughnuts, General Porpoise serves top-quality coffees from multiple roasters. Espresso, pour-over, drip, and cold draft brew are all available.' From the Eater website, 'Renowned restaurateur Renee Erickson has wowed dessert aficionados with British-influenced doughnuts at this cozy E Union Street locale: fresh custards, sweet creams, and homemade jams made from locally sourced ingredients. In addition to Capitol Hill, there are outposts in Laurelhurst and Pioneer Square.' Let’s Be Us (YouTube) recommends them because all they do is filled donuts with different seasonal jams, custards, etc. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Great State Burger
posts.note: Great State Burger is a Washington-focused burger joint serving local organic beef and shakes in hip digs. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Harbor City Restaurant
posts.note: Harbor City Restaurant is a casual family-owned Chinese restaurant serving dim sum, Peking duck, congee and other favorites. I ordered five different types of dumplings along with some wide noodles with beef and a quarter of a roast duck.

posts.name: The Herbfarm
posts.note: The Herbfarm serves a fixed-price, 9-course menu paired with local wine at a bucolic culinary retreat attached to an inn. From their website, 'The Herbfarm, a World Rich in Country Charm. Designed and created from artwork and objects gathered from throughout the world, The Herbfarm Restaurant invites you to an evening of exciting dining in rich and comfortable surroundings. An optional pre-dinner Wine Cellar Open House begins 50 minutes before each dinner seating. In addition, an introduction to The Herbfarm and outdoor hosted garden tour begins 30 minutes before service each evening.'

posts.name: homegrown
posts.note: homegrown is a local counter-serve chain offering a menu of artisan sandwiches, soups, and salads in a hip setting. I ordered their Two Fried Eggs Bowl which is two pasture-raised fried eggs, applewood bacon, harissa home fries, caramelized onion, roasted red pepper, braised farm greens, and chermoula aioli on the side. I also tried their Bacon, Egg, and Cheese Sandwich which is applewood bacon, pasture-raised fried egg, Beecher's cheese, and roasted garlic aioli. NOTE: They have multiple locations around the Seattle area.

posts.name: Ivar's Acres of Clams
posts.note: Ivar's Acres of Clams is a local chain dishing up fried fish and chowders in casual quarters with nautical accents. NOTE: They have several other locations even one located in the Seattle-Tacoma International Airport.

posts.name: Joule
posts.note: Joule is a Korean-fusion steakhouse offering Asian-Northwest eats amid handmade wallpaper and communal seating. From their website, 'Rachel Yang and Seif Chirchi opened their first restaurant, Joule, to critical acclaim in 2007. The food—a confident, beautiful blend of Korean flavors and classic technique—earned them a reputation as culinary innovators and creative forces. In 2013, they reimagined Joule as a contemporary Korean steakhouse serving nontraditional cuts of beef and reopened it in an expanded space. The same year, it was named one of the Best New Restaurants in America by Bon Appétit magazine.'

posts.name: Kamonegi
posts.note: From the Eater website about Kamonegi, 'Exceptional new restaurants sometimes rouse an old question: In cooking, where’s the line between art and craft? The fine points certainly blur at Kamonegi, where Mutsuko Soma, who learned how to make soba from her grandmother, does so entirely from scratch. She starts by grinding buckwheat (usually grown locally) to make the flour for the noodles over which she labors daily. These strands, at once taut and delicate, are practically sentient in their freshness. Begin first with tempura, nearly equal to the soba, with unorthodox but brilliant combinations like broccolini accented with Parmesan and miso-anchovy aioli. The soba comes in three variations: cold with a cold dipping sauce, hot in broth, and as “shrimpcado bukkake,” an intricate noodle bowl that includes shrimp tempura, avocado, and grated radish. I ordered all of them; the server returned and very politely said, “The chef wants to make sure there’s enough soba for every customer. Could you please choose two out of the three options?” I didn’t balk, and I passed on the cold version. I wouldn’t want a soul to miss out on Soma’s masterwork.'
posts.rcmmnd: Eater's 18 Best New Restaurants in America - 2018

posts.name: Kastoori Grill
posts.note: Kastoori Grill is a casual restaurant specializing in Indian and Tibetan fare with a lunch buffet and vegetarian options. Went during lunch and had their buffet. I enjoyed the different types of mixed vegetables along with the curry chicken and the lamb curry.

posts.name: Kidd Valley
posts.note: Kidd Valley is a counter-serve chain offering burgers and sandwiches, along with fried mushrooms, onion rings, shakes, and more. From their website, 'With locations throughout Puget Sound, Kidd Valley has earned a loyal following for its made-to-order burgers, old-fashioned hand-mixed shakes, and mouthwatering side dishes like fresh sweet onion rings and signature fried mushrooms. Not a beef or meat-eater? Or have gluten issues? No problem! Kidd Valley offers delicious vegan burgers and garden burgers. And all burger-lovers can choose between our signature, wheat or gluten-free buns.' From the Seattle Eater website, 'If you’re near the Kidd when you’re thirsty, get one of their creamy root beer milkshakes, or the chilly boysenberry, strawberry or pineapple shakes, which have chunks of fruit in them.' Dylan Wilbanks recommends the double-bacon cheeseburger.

posts.name: Kizuki Ramen and Izakaya
posts.note: Kizuki Ramen and Izakaya is a hip ramen shop is a local branch of a Tokyo chain, with modern steel-and-wood surrounds. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Le Panier
posts.note: Le Panier serves handcrafted goodies run the gamut from fresh-baked bread to macarons, all made in a French style. Their bread is used at Uli's Famous Sausage in Pikes Place Market.

posts.name: Li'l Woody's
posts.note: Li'l Woody's serves burgers in many combos plus homemade shakes served in a rustic yet lively space that's open late. I ordered the Li'l Woody is a quarter pound Painted Hills grass-fed beef burger, Tillamook cheddar, chopped onions, diced pickles, ketchup, and mayo with a side of fries which were huge. Also, thought of getting the Fig and the Pig which is a third of a pound Painted Hills grass-fed beef burger, a scoop of their pickled figs, Hills bacon, and crumbled blue cheese. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Local Color
posts.note: Local Color has art displayed on the walls of this casual coffee shop with a range of pastries and light bites. They have great coffee, and I'm not a coffee person by any means. The locals and workers at Pike Place Market get their coffee here.

posts.name: Maneki
posts.note: Maneki is a landmark Japanese spot dating back to 1904 with tatami rooms, a bar, and classic fare including sushi.

posts.name: Marination Ma Kai
posts.note: Marination Ma Kai has a few food trucks and a brick-and-mortar space for Hawaiian-Korean fusion fare, breakfast, bar, and dockside patio. From their website, 'In 2009, fresh off a big market crash, Marination owners Kamala and Roz decided on a new kind of investment: running their own business. Big Blue took to the streets in June, with smiles for miles and a unique Hawaiian-Korean fusion cuisine in tow. The people have spoken again and again about how our spicy, tangy, sweet, and aloha-laden fare brightens their day (if not the whole week!)' From the Seattle Eater website, 'Though this popular mini-chain has pared down its operation during the pandemic (closing its Capitol Hill location), the West Seattle flagship is still open for takeout and some limited outdoor seating. It’s hard to go wrong with the menu’s flavorful Hawaiian-Korean fusion fare, including the superb miso ginger chicken and kalbi beef options with Nunya sauce.' NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Marination Station
posts.note: Marination Station is a cool Hawaiian-Korean spot doling out tacos, sliders, and kimchi rice bowls. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Marrakesh Moroccan Restaurant
posts.note: Marrakesh Moroccan Restaurant were patrons sit on pillows amid tent like decor and eat Moroccan dishes such as couscous with their hands.

posts.name: Mee Sum Pastry
posts.note: Mee Sum Pastry is a no-frills food stand offering buns, pastries and other Chinese grub in digs by the Pike Place Market.

posts.name: Melrose Market
posts.note: Situated at the west end of the Pike-Pine neighborhood, Melrose Market is an indoor food and retail market on Capitol Hill in Seattle. It occupies a set of historic automotive buildings constructed between 1919 and 1926, which were ultimately converted into the Melrose Market. Had breakfast at homegrown while I was there and ordered their 'Two Fried Eggs Bowl' and a half of the 'Bacon, Egg, and Cheese Sandwich'.

posts.name: Mighty-O Donuts
posts.note: Husband-and-wife owners Ryan Kellner and Megan Helmer opened their first Mighty-O cafe in 2003, and their creations are about as virtuous as doughnuts can be, with GMO-free, certified organic, and trans-fat free ingredients complementing the vegan approach. The cafes donate all leftovers to the homeless and support local schools and the nonprofit Food Lifeline. I ordered the apple fritter with a generous amount of cinnamon and a great chew along with the chocolate glazed peanut cake donut. Top five apple fritter ever and best peanut cake donut in every long time. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Mike's Chili Parlor
posts.note: Mike's Chili Parlor is a tiny, low-key, family-owned eatery and bar serving burgers, hot dogs, and its signature chili since 1922.

posts.name: Momiji
posts.note: Momiji is a stylish Japanese restaurant for sushi and upscale cocktails in a serene space with a Kyoto courtyard. From their website, 'Momiji is a hand-crafted Japanese restaurant located in Seattle's Capitol Hill neighborhood. We have a courtyard that's an oasis in the bustling neighborhood. Our menu features sushi, rolls, omakase, and other traditional Japanese foods prepared from great Northwest ingredients. Our courtyard will be an oasis in the bustling neighborhood of Capitol Hill.'

posts.name: Nishino
posts.note: Nishino is known for its omakase menu; this low-key Japanese choice has inventive sushi in an art-filled space. From their website, 'Located steps away from Seattle's beautiful arboretum park, Nishino has been serving traditional and innovative Japanese cuisine since 1995. We invite you to come experience for yourself the finest sushi restaurant in the city.'

posts.name: Owl and Thistle
posts.note: Owl and Thistle is a Dublin-style pub with live music most nights and a house band playing Irish music most weekends. It's truly a dive bar near the ferry station and a way from Pike's Place Market.

posts.name: Pacific Inn Pub
posts.note: Pacific Inn Pub serves microbrews and bar food offered in a compact diner with modest decor along with a pool table. You need to order the fish n chips.

posts.name: Pam’s Kitchen
posts.note: Pam’s Kitchen relaxed Trinidadian-Caribbean eatery serving jerk chicken and curries, plus juices and cocktails. You need to order the curry goat, Spicy Jerk Chicken and Pelau which is similar to jambalaya or Dahlpuri, an unleavened bread stuffed with yellow split peas, then rolled up and cooked to order on the flattop.

posts.name: Paseo (Fremont)
posts.note: Paseo (Fremont) is counter-service Caribbean joint serving sandwiches and entrees in a simple setting. From their website, 'You don't have to go to NYC or LA to find a great sandwich. Last year, Thrillist included Paseo on their list of the 31 best sandwich shops in the USA. Why, because all of our bodacious sandwiches and platters are bursting with Caribbean flavors and made only with locally sourced ingredients right here in Seattle. The Paseo Caribbean Roast is a legendary and beloved Seattle sandwich. Bursting with intense flavors, the Caribbean Roast harmonizes juicy roasted pulled pork shoulder, aioli, cilantro, romaine, jalapeños, and caramelized onions.' NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Pasta Casalinga
posts.note: Pasta Casalinga is an Italian spot in Pikes Place Market for their handcrafted pastas and wine served in a petite space amidst the bustling market.

posts.name: Pike Place Market
posts.note: Pike Place Market is a public market overlooking the Elliott Bay waterfront in Seattle, Washington, United States. The Market opened August 17, 1907, and is one of the oldest continuously operated public farmers' markets in the United States.

posts.name: Piroshki on 3rd
posts.note: Piroshki on 3rd serves savory and sweet Russian turnovers (Piroshki) along 20 different varieties of the savory, pastry-wrapped pockets which are their specialty at this counter-serve cafe. They are also dishing out traditional soups, dumplings, salads and more. The piroshki are great, but the thing to order is the Pelmeni which is chicken-filled dumplings in a steaming broth.

posts.name: Piroshky Piroshky
posts.note: Piroshky Piroshky is a compact Russian bakery located in Pike Place Market serving over 20 varieties of handmade piroshki.

posts.name: Pizzeria Credo
posts.note: Pizzeria Credo serves wood-fired Neapolitan pizzas, and housemade mozzarella are prepared at this buzzy Italian bar and parlor. You should order tagliatelle bolognese or the Poulet Vallee d’Auge (creamy chicken with apples and mushrooms).

posts.name: Plum Bistro
posts.note: Plum Bistro is an organic, sustainable vegan dishes featuring seitan and tofu in an industrial-chic space. Heard chef and owner Makini Howell talk on Live Wire on NPR about and her mother's vegan restaurant.

posts.name: Princi Bakery
posts.note: Princi Bakery which is inside the Seattle Reserve Starbucks and makes phenomenal baked goods. I got one of their hand-crafted pizzas which are on a focaccia base, brushed with housemade pomodoro sauce and topped with premium ingredients like mozzarella di bufala, speck and scamorza, roasted eggplant and colorful peppers. Get the chocolate ganache tart.

posts.name: Quinn's Pub
posts.note: Quinn's Pub is a hip gastropub for artisanal eats and a curated beer selection in a renovated bi-level storefront.

posts.name: Rainier Restaurant and BBQ
posts.add1: 6400 Martin Luther King Jr Way S
posts.note: Rainier Restaurant and BBQ serve homestyle Vietnamese cooking is offered in a simple setting with an adjacent deli serving banh mi.

posts.name: Revel
posts.note: Revel serves Korean dishes prepared with French technique in a modern industrial-design space with a hopping bar. You need to try the Short rib, pickled shallot, scallion dumplings

posts.name: Salt and Straw
posts.note: Salt and Straw is a Portland-based Salt and Straw, renowned for its inventive ice cream flavor combinations. I tend to order their 'Sea Salt with Caramel Ribbons' every time I'm there it that good. One critic said, 'Salt and Straw is a West Coast chain serving the best ice cream you can get in the city, let alone Capitol Hill.' NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Salumi
posts.note: Salumi is a tiny storefront offering artisanal Italian cured meats in sandwiches and by the pound. Salumi is owned and operated by Mario Batali's father. When I was there recently, I ordered their pork ragu with spaghetti for my lunch along with a meatball sandwich fresh mozzarella cheese and a roasted lamb sandwich to have for dinner over two nights. I managed to grab a few different salumi's to take back home with me. One being their Mole and if I didn't bring any home many of my friends were going to disown me. NOTE: They close at 3:30 PM most days or when they ran out of bread, but things could have changed.

posts.name: Sea Breeze Farms - La Boucherie
posts.note: Sea Breeze Farms - La Boucherie is a rural destination offering farm-to-table dinners from seasonal ingredients in a cozy environment.

posts.name: Seatown Seabar
posts.note: Seatown Seabar is an eat-in deli at Pike Place Market with seafood, sandwiches & rotisserie meats, plus an outdoor patio.

posts.name: Seattle Coffee Works
posts.note: Seattle Coffee Works is an unpretentious coffeehouse with an espresso bar and a slow bar for comparing single-origin beans. It's a nice bastion of quiet in the madness that is Pike Place Market.

posts.name: Serious Pie
posts.note: Serious Pie is a cozy restaurant with wood-fired, thin-crust gourmet pizzas, wine, and beer served at communal tables. From their website, 'Serious Pie, pizzeria with a bread baker's soul, serves up pies with blistered crusts, light textured but with just enough structure and bite. Our attentiveness to each pizza in the 600-degree stone-encased apple wood-burning oven preserves the character of house-made charcuterie and artisan cheeses from around the world. Our dough is hand-crafted through a multiple day process, which gives it the complexity. The crust is then blistered in 600-degree heat until lightly browned. They are then topped with things like housemade charcuterie, foraged mushrooms, and imported cheeses. We source fresh vegetables and herbs from Prosser, Washington, which utilizes the bounty of the Pacific Northwest.'

posts.name: Shiro's Sushi
posts.note: Shiro's Sushi serves omakase and an à la carte menu in a spartan room at this prominent Belltown fixture. It's the first 'Edomae' sushi restaurant in Seattle.

posts.name: Shorty's
posts.note: Shorty's is a bit of dive bar that is Coney Island-themed and a favorite hangout, offering hot dogs, nachos, pinball, and arcade games.

posts.name: Sisters And Brothers
posts.note: Sisters And Brothers is a bright storefront dishing up Nashville hot chicken plus other Southern-inspired fare. They are known for their Nashville Hot Chicken or the bacon Mac and cheese with smoked Gouda.

posts.name: Smarty Pants
posts.note: Smarty Pants is a laid-back restaurant offering scratch-made comfort foods, craft beers, which has a motorcycle-themed decor. From their website, 'In addition to the sandwiches, we make homemade soups, chili, a variety of salads, and dressings daily. We also can make any of our selections vegetarian or vegan with locally-made Field Roast, a fresh and natural grain meat.'

posts.name: Soulful Dishes
posts.note: Soulful Dishes is a Central District soul food spot that serves fried chicken sandwiches, burgers and fries, fried catfish, and more.

posts.name: Storyville Coffee Pike Place
posts.note: Storyville Coffee Pike Place is a market-based spot for artisanal coffee and baked goods in stylish wood-clad digs with a fireplace. Let’s Be Us (YouTube) says they have great coffee, but the thing to buy is their chocolate chip cookie. From their website, 'We are on the top floor of the Corner Market building at First and Pike in Pike Place Market. Stand on the red cobblestone and look toward the iconic red neon “Public Market Center” clock-sign. Our building will be on your right. Take the stairs or the elevator to the top floor.'

posts.name: Sushi Kappo Tamura
posts.note: Sushi Kappo Tamura is an upscale Japanese spot serving sushi and cocktails in an elegant, modern space with an open kitchen. From their website, 'Using local and seasonal ingredients is the most important element in Japanese cuisine. It also has become the primary principle for the international culinary community. With a commitment to that philosophy, Sushi Kappo Tamura features seasonal ingredients of the Pacific Northwest in authentic Japanese preparation. Tamura is a Kappo style restaurant where food is prepared in an open kitchen and served quickly in a lively environment where staff and guests talk about the food and beyond. Our goal is to become the very best restaurant to our guests by getting to know them and serving them in a personable yet professional manner.'

posts.name: TAT'S Delicatessen
posts.note: TAT'S Delicatessen is a busy lunchtime spot known for Philly cheesesteaks, subs, and soups, also serving breakfast in the AM.

posts.name: Taylor Oyster Bar
posts.note: Taylor Shellfish Oyster Bar is a casual seafood specialist known for fresh shellfish offers a full bar with craft brews on tap. You should order the deep fried smelt. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Tilth Restaurant
posts.note: Tilth Restaurant is Maria Hines' sustainable, seasonal American fare in a Craftsman house makes it a foodie hot spot. From their website, 'We feature New American cuisine prepared with certified-organic or wild ingredients sourced from as many local farmers we are able to support. Our chef and owner, Maria Hines, is a James Beard Award winner for Best Chef of the Northwest, as well as one of Food and Wine Magazine’s 10 Best New Chefs of 2005. In 2008, the New York Times deemed Tilth one of the best new restaurants in the country. Tilth received its organic certification from Oregon Tilth, an unaffiliated organization that promotes sustainability.

posts.name: Top Pot Doughnuts
posts.note: Top Pot Doughnuts is a local chain, and they invited you to join them on their delicious journey of good taste. From their uniquely designed cafés to their hand-roasted coffee and hand-forged gourmet doughnuts. Top Pot Doughnuts is committed to doing things the old-fashioned way—beautifully, warmly, and with unfailing attention to details. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: Victrola Coffee Roasters
posts.note: Victrola Coffee Roasters is a relaxed coffeehouse with vintage decor offering global coffees, weekly tastings, and pastries. It's located about a half a block from the Starbucks Reserve Roastery and is a great place to relax and get work done. NOTE: They have multiple locations.

posts.name: The Walrus and the Carpenter
posts.note: The Walrus and the Carpenter serve oysters and other seafood plus American plates along with specialty cocktails in a small, simple space.

posts.name: Wasabi Sushi and Izakaya
posts.note: Wasabi Sushi and Izakaya serves creative sushi, and new takes on Japanese cooking in a stylish, modern space with a young, upbeat vibe.

posts.name: Westman's Bagel and Coffee
posts.note: Westman's Bagel and Coffee is a sidewalk cafe stop dishing up fresh bagels, schmears of cream cheese, and coffee. The shop is located on the side of the outside of a building, and it's four or six feet deep and about 20 feet long with a handful of metal stools. From what I could find out on the internet it's 300 sq feet. So more like 15 feet by 20 feet or maybe 12 feet by 25 feet with the cooking/baking part in the back and out of sight.
